<title type="html"><![CDATA[apu clock jitter]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=3926&amp;p=31152#p31152"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />The test rom 04.clock_jitter.nes reads 4015h at 29831, no matter the even/odd state.<br /></div><br />Yes, exactly. If the $4017 write occurs on an even APU clock, the read will find the flag set. If on an odd APU clock, the flag won't be set yet. Hence the name of the routine, get_jitter.<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">get_jitter:<br />...<br />lda #$00   ; begin mode 0, frame irq enabled<br />sta $4017<br />delay 29827<br />lda $4015   ; read at 29831<br />and #$40<br />rts</div><br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />I didn't get, should 4015h return 0 instead of 40h to pass?<br /></div><br />Let's stick to behavior tested. I don't want to get into the endless detail of how the test ROMs work. I think there's some kind of barrier preventing this from working. It might be language, development style, I don't know, but it's very tiring and nothing ever makes much sense. Bleah. Without a clean approach, it becomes a big mess.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=17">blargg</a> — Fri Feb 22, 2008 7:44 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
